==Center for Inquiry== ''Point of Inquiry'' is the premiere [[podcast]] production of the [[Center for Inquiry]] (CFI), a non-profit educational organization located in the United States. Its primary mission is to encourage evidence-based inquiry into [[paranormal]] and [[fringe science]] claims, [[alternative medicine]] and mental health practices, religion, [[secular ethics]], and society. CFI is dedicated to promoting and defending science, reason, and free inquiry in all aspects of human interest. CFI has also produced two related podcasts titled "The Human Bible" and "Center Stage," both of which have ended.
==Popular Science Idol== Point of inquiry co-sponsored the "Popular Science Idol"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nsfmessengers.wordpress.com/2013/01/25/do-you-have-what-it-takes-to-be-americas-next-science-idol/|title=Do You Have What It Takes to Be America’s Next Science Idol?|date= 10 March 2013}}</ref> contest along with the National Science Foundation Office of Legislative and Public Affairs, Discover Magazine, and Popular Science as a science spoof of the popular reality show American Idol. The event was hosted as a workshop to discover the next great science communicator. The event was hosted by Chris Mooney and Indre Viskontas served as one of the expert judges. The first event was won by Tom Di Loberto for a 3-minute presentation on the difficulties involved in predicting the weather.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scpr.org/programs/take-two/2013/02/19/30577/meteorologist-wins-first-ever-americas-science-ido/|title=Meteorologist wins first-ever America's Science Idol competition|date= 10 March 2013 }}</ref>
